England, United Kingdom":"Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Middleton, Westmorland, England":"Middleton, Westmorland, England","Wormington, Gloucestershire, England":"Wormington, Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Middleton Hall, Westmoreland, England":"Middleton, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kirkham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly northwestern): habitational name from any of the places in Lancashire and East Yorkshire named Kirkham. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>kirkja</i> ‘church’ + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or Old Norse <i>heim</i> ‘homestead, estate’.","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Kirchham</b>, a habitational name from either of two places called Kirchham, in Austria or Bavaria."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Margaret Kirkham was born in 1484, in Wormington, Gloucestershire, England, her father, George Kirkham, was 35 and her mother, Anne Armeston, was 22. She married Sir Geoffrey Middleton in 1499, in Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1515, in England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1484–1515":"1484–1515","1485–Male":"1485–Surnud","1496–1558":"1496–1558","1500–1566":"1500–1566","1512–1543":"1512–1543","1480–1545":"1480–1545","1485–1570":"1485–1570","1507–1580":"1507–1580","–Male":"Surnud","1449–1528":"1449–1528","1462–Female":"1462–Surnud","1484":"1484","1462":"1462","1570":"1570","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","about 1507":"umbes 1507","1558":"1558","1545":"1545","1512":"1512","1566":"1566","1500